# History: tooling-docker-headless-build-credential-helper

This file preserves the full original content of prior versions of
`tooling-docker-headless-build-credential-helper` before each amendment.

## v1.1.0 (2026-07-06)

**Changed by:** Claude Sonnet 5 (`/learn` session, debugging category)

**Verification:** verified-local

**What changed:** Extended the skill from "docker build over SSH" to also cover
`docker compose pull`/`up` failing under `sudo` (or any non-desktop shell context)
with the same D-Bus/X11 credential error, even when there is NO `~/.docker/config.json`
file at all. Added to `## Overview` (root cause now explicitly covers auto-detection of
any `docker-credential-*` binary in `PATH` when no config file exists at all, not only when
`credsStore` is explicitly set), `## When to Use` (sudo/non-desktop trigger, docker compose
trigger), `## Verified Workflow` (explicit `credsStore: ""` fix as the reliable persistent-config
approach, alongside the existing temp-`DOCKER_CONFIG`-override approach for one-off builds;
note that `docker compose` has a separate credential-resolution code path from `docker pull`
and must be verified independently), and `## Failed Attempts` (four new rows documenting the
sudo/compose-specific traps). Bumped `version` 1.0.0 → 1.1.0 (MINOR — additive scope, no
removal/contradiction of prior guidance), `date` → 2026-07-06, added tags `docker-compose`,
`sudo`, `dbus`, `credsstore`. Added `history: tooling-docker-headless-build-credential-helper.history`
to frontmatter (first amendment).

**Why:** On a Debian/PureOS homelab host with a full desktop environment installed (GNOME-keyring
packages present), running several `docker compose pull <service>` commands via `sudo bash
script.sh` (as root) all failed identically with the D-Bus/X11 credential-helper error, even
immediately after confirming `docker pull hello-world` succeeded as root. Investigation revealed
two traps stacked on the original finding: (1) Docker auto-detects and invokes any
`docker-credential-*` binary present in `PATH` whenever no `~/.docker/config.json` exists at
all for that user — this is not limited to when `credsStore` is explicitly configured, so
"no config file" does not mean "no credential helper attempted"; (2) `docker compose` (the
separate Go plugin `docker-compose` under `cli-plugins`) has its own credential-resolution path
independent of the plain `docker` CLI, so fixing `docker pull` for a user does not prove
`docker compose pull` is fixed for that same user, and fixing one user/UID context (e.g. root)
does not fix a different context reached via `sudo -u otheruser ...` from within a root script,
because that sub-shell has no inherited D-Bus session either. The reliable fix is to explicitly
write `credsStore: ""` (not merely omit the key) into `~/.docker/config.json` for every distinct
user/UID context that actually invokes docker/compose, and to verify `docker compose pull`
directly rather than trusting a passing `docker pull` as sufficient proof.

